# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: door-breaching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The **75th Ranger Regiment**, also known as the **Rangers**, is the United States Army Special Operations Command's premier special operations infantry force.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The regiment is headquartered at Fort Benning, Georgia, and comprises a regimental headquarters company, a military intelligence battalion, a special troops battalion, and three Ranger battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 75th Ranger Regiment primarily handles direct-action raids in hostile or sensitive environments, often killing or capturing high-value targets.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Other missions include airfield seizure, special reconnaissance, personnel recovery, clandestine insertion, and site exploitation.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The regiment can deploy one Ranger battalion within 18 hours of alert notification.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The regiment's subunit the Regimental Reconnaissance Company is part of Joint Special Operations Command.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 75th Ranger Regiment is one of the U.S. military's most extensively used units.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 17 December 2020, it marked 7,000 consecutive days of combat operations.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] American Ranger history predates the American Revolutionary War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Captain Benjamin Church formed Church's Rangers, which fought hostile Native American tribes during King Philip's War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 1756, Robert Rogers recruited nine Ranger companies to fight in the French and Indian War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 75th Regiment's history dates back to these rifle companies organized by Rogers, which made long-range attacks against French forces and their native allies, and were instrumental in capturing Fort Detroit.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the American Revolutionary War, Rogers served as a Loyalist officer on the side of the Crown and many of his former Rangers served on both sides.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] One, John Stark, commanded the 1st New Hampshire Regiment, which gained fame at the Battles of Bunker Hill and Bennington.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Ethan Allen and his Green Mountain Boys in Vermont were also designated as a ranger unit.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 1775, the Continental Congress later formed eight companies of expert riflemen to fight in the Revolutionary War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 1777, this force commanded by Daniel Morgan, was known as The Corps of Rangers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Francis Marion, "The Swamp Fox", organized another famous Revolutionary War Ranger element known as "Marion's Partisans".
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Perhaps the most famous Ranger unit in the Revolutionary War was Butler's Rangers, from upstate New York.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the War of 1812, companies of United States Rangers were raised from among the frontier settlers as part of the regular army.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Throughout the war, they patrolled the frontier from Ohio to Western Illinois on horseback and by boat.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Rangers participated in many skirmishes and battles with the British and their American Indian allies.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Various military Ranger units such as the United States Mounted Rangers, United States Rangers, Loudoun Rangers, 43rd Virginia Rangers, and Texas Military Rangers continued until the modern formation of the Army Ranger Battalions in World War II.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Soon after the United States entered World War II in 1941, General George C.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Marshall, Chief of Staff of the United States Army, envisioned an elite unit of fifty men selected voluntarily from the 34th Infantry Division.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] To create and lead this new unit, Marshall picked Major William Orlando Darby, who was serving as General Russell P.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Hartle's aide in Belfast, Northern Ireland, where he was frustrated with his lack of hands-on experience.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 8 June 1942, Darby—now known as the founder of the modern Rangers—was put in charge of the 1st Ranger Battalion under General Hartle.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 19 August 1942, fifty Rangers fought alongside Canadian and British Commandos in the ill-fated Dieppe Raid on the coast of occupied France.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Three Rangers were killed and several were captured.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The first American soldier killed in Europe in World War II, Ranger Lieutenant E.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the mission, Loustalot took command after the British captain leading the assault was killed.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] While attempting to reach a machine gun nest at the top of a cliff, he was wounded three times by enemy fire and killed.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In November 1942, the entire 1st Ranger Battalion entered combat for the first time when they landed at Arzew, Algeria during Operation Torch.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 1st were split into two groups in hopes of assaulting Vichy-French batteries and fortifications before the 1st Infantry Division would land on the beach.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The operation was successful, and the unit sustained minimal casualties.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 11 February 1943, the Rangers moved 32 miles (51 km) to raid an Italian encampment at Sened Station.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Moving at night, the Rangers slipped to within 50 yards (46 m) of the Italian outpost and began their attack.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] It took the battalion only 20 minutes to overtake the garrison and achieve their objective.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Seventy-five Italians were killed and eleven were taken prisoner.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Darby, along with four other officers and nine enlisted, was awarded the Silver Star Medal for this action.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The battalion itself gained the nickname the "Black Death" by the Italians.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] At the time, the Italians still held the pass at Djebel El Ank, located at the far east edge of El Guettar.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers linked up with engineers elements of the 26th Infantry, 1st Infantry Division, to attack the area in preparation for the Battle of El Guettar.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 1st Rangers orders were to move overland, on foot 12 miles (19 km) to outflank the enemy's position.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In eight hours of fighting, the Americans captured the objective; the 1st Rangers took 200 prisoners.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] With the success of the 1st Ranger Battalion during the Tunisian campaign, Darby requested that the Rangers be expanded to a full Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 3rd and 4th Ranger Battalions were authorized shortly after and were trained and led by veteran officers and NCOs from the 1st Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After getting the "green light" to expand, Darby ran into a problem: the Rangers only took volunteers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Darby, knowing that the best man for the job was not always a volunteer, sought out men around Oran.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Although he was still limited in that he could only accept volunteers, he began to find ways around this.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] For instance, he began to give speeches, put up posters, and encourage his officers to scout around for eligible candidates.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By June 1943, the three Ranger battalions were fully operational.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] 1st Rangers were still under Colonel Darby; the 3rd Rangers under Major Herman Dammer, and the 4th Rangers commanded by Major Roy Murray.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] 1st and 4th Ranger Battalions were paired together and placed with General Terry Allen's 1st Division to spearhead the American landings of the Sicily campaign.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Landing outside Gela, the Rangers took the town just after midnight, starting off the Battle of Gela.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They held Gela, enduring 50 hours of constant attack by enemy artillery, tank, and air forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Following their success, the two Ranger battalions were then ordered to take the town of Butera, a fortress suspended on the 1,319-foot (402 m) high edge of the cliff at Butera beach.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After almost withdrawing from the battle, and requesting artillery to level the city, a platoon of Rangers volunteered to breach its defenses.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Two privates, John See and John Constantine, snuck in behind enemy lines and tricked the Italians and Germans into surrendering the city.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Meanwhile, the 3rd Ranger Battalion headed out into the area of Agrigento, where they marched through Campobello, Naro, and Favara, successfully occupying each town.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 3rd then took the town of Porto Empedocle.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Colonel Darby was awarded the Distinguished Service Cross and was promoted by General George Patton; however, Darby, wanting to be closer to his men, turned down this promotion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After a break for Christmas 1943, the Rangers were put together for a joint effort to occupy the town of Cisterna before the main infantry division moved in.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On the night of 30 January 1944, the 1st and 3rd battalions moved into the town, passing many German soldiers who did not appear to notice the Rangers slip by.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 4th Ranger Battalion, which approached the town from the opposite end, met opposition almost immediately on the road.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the night, the 1st and 3rd Ranger battalions separated by about 2 miles (3.2 km), and when daylight caught the 1st Ranger Battalion out in an open field, the Germans began their ambush.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Surrounded and unable to escape, the two Ranger battalions fought on until they exhausted their ammunition and resources.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 4th Ranger Battalion pushed to save their comrades but were forced to withdraw.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After five hours of fighting, the Rangers surrendered to the German armor and mechanized infantry.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The two battalions sustained 12 killed, 36 wounded, and 743 captured—only eight were able to escape.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 4th Battalion suffered 30 killed and 58 wounded.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] This marked the end of the three Ranger battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The remaining 400 Rangers were scattered around the 504th Parachute Infantry Regiment, and the 137 original Rangers were sent home.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] 1st and 3rd Battalions were disbanded on 15 August 1944, while 4th Battalion was disbanded on 24 October 1944, at Camp Butner, North Carolina.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd Ranger Battalion and 5th Ranger Battalion were trained at Camp Forrest, Tennessee, on 1 April 1943.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They first saw action 6 June 1944, during Operation Overlord.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During D-day 2nd Rangers companies D, E, and F, were ordered to take a strategic German outpost at Pointe du Hoc.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] This coastal cliff was supposed to have several 155 mm artillery cannons aimed down at the beach.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Once they arrived at the bottom of the cliff, they had an enormous climb to make up rope ladders while receiving a barrage of machinegun fire from the Germans above.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd Rangers took the area even with the intense German resistance but the guns were not in sight.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A patrol scouting the area found the 155 mm coastal guns a mile away; the patrol party quickly disabled the guns and resistance in the area.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Meanwhile, the rest of the 2nd and 5th Ranger Battalions spearheaded the attack on the beach at Omaha.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] An apocryphal story tells of when General Norman Cota, leading the 29th Infantry Division, met with Major Max F.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Schneider, commanding the 5th Ranger Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] When Schneider was asked his unit by Cota, someone yelled out "5th Rangers!", to which Cota replied, "Well then Goddammit, Rangers, lead the way!" This drive cut the German line allowing the conventional army to move in.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The phrase "Rangers lead the way" later became the motto of the regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd and 5th Ranger Battalions worked on special operation tasks in the Normandy Campaign.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The two battalions fought in many battles such as Battle for Brest and the Battle of the Hurtgen Forest.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd Rangers were responsible for capturing Le Conquet Peninsula, where they disabled a 280 mm gun and took many German prisoners.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd Ranger Battalion also went on to take several tactical German positions, cutting the German line in the Rhineland.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In Saar west of Zerf, the 5th Battalion took an overlooking German position cutting of all supply routes to German forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 6th Ranger Battalion was stationed in the Pacific, and served mostly in the Philippines and New Guinea.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] All operations completed by the 6th Battalion were done in company- or platoon-size behind enemy lines.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They were the first soldiers to hit the Philippines, three days before the army would launch the first invasion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 6th Ranger Battalion conducted long-range reconnaissance, operating miles past the front line.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] At Cabanatuan, on the island of Luzon in January 1945, a company of the 6th Ranger Battalion executed the Raid at Cabanatuan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers penetrated 22–24 miles (35–39 km) behind enemy lines, including crawling a mile (1 mile (1.6 km)) across an open field on their stomachs.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During their final assault the Rangers destroyed a garrison of Japanese soldiers twice their size and rescued 500 POWs.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 6th Ranger Battalion's final mission was to secure a drop zone for 11th Airborne Division paratroopers 250 miles (400 km) into enemy territory.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They linked up with the 37th Infantry Division and ended the war in the Philippines.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In August 1944, after five months of fighting in China Burma India Theater with the Japanese Army, Merrill's Marauders (5307th Composite Unit (Provisional)) were consolidated into then 475th Infantry, afterwards the 75th Infantry Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] As a special force group led by Brigadier General Frank Merrill, to commemorate its companion Chinese Expeditionary Force (Burma), Merrill's Marauders put the sun from the National emblem of the Republic of China and the Star from Burma's flag on its badge.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The lightning bolt signifies the swiftness of their strikes.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Merrill's Marauders would later become part of the regiment's lineage.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The outbreak of hostilities in Korea in June 1950 again signaled the need for Rangers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Fifteen Ranger companies were formed during the Korean War, drawing their lineages from the World War II era Ranger battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers went to battle throughout the winter of 1950 and the spring of 1951.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They were nomadic warriors, attached first to one Regiment and then to another.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They performed "out front" work—scouting, patrolling, raids, ambushes, spearheading assaults, and as counterattack forces to regain lost positions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In all six airborne Ranger companies, the 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th, and 8th, averaging 125 soldiers in each company served during the conflict.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Two other companies, the 10th and 11th, were scheduled for Korea but were deactivated in Japan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the course of the Korean War, 100 Rangers were killed in action and 296 were wounded in action.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Despite sharing a similar name, these Ranger units under the 75th Infantry Regiment (Ranger) drew their lineages not from the World War II/Korean War era Ranger battalions but from 5307 Composite Unit, also known as Merrill's Marauders.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 1974, their colors and lineage were passed to newly formed Ranger Battalions based in the United States.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The first period above began in Vietnam in November 1966 with the creation of a provisional LRRP Detachment by the 1st Cavalry Division (Airmobile); followed by the 1st Brigade, 101st Airborne Division; the 1st Infantry Division; and the 25th Infantry Division in June 1966.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Westmoreland, commander of Military Assistance Command, Vietnam (MACV), ordered the creation of provisional LRRPs in all Infantry brigades and divisions on 8 July 1966.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By the winter of 1966 the 4th and 9th Infantry Divisions had operational LRRP units, and in January 1967 the 196th Light Infantry Brigade had the same.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 101st Airborne Division "main body," while still at Fort Campbell, Kentucky, converted its divisional Recondo School into a provisional LRRP unit in the summer of 1967, before the division deployed to Vietnam.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] This provisional company arrived in Vietnam in late November 1967.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The second period began in late June 1967, when the chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, General Earle G.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Wheeler, authorized the formation of two long-range patrol companies for I and II Field Forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Company E (Long Range Reconnaissance Patrol), 20th Infantry (Airborne) was activated on 25 September 1967, and assigned to I Field Force and stationed at Phan Rang.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The nucleus of this unit came from the 1st Brigade, 101st Airborne Division LRRP Platoon, along with soldiers from the replacement stream.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Company F (Long Range Patrol), 51st Infantry (Airborne) was activated on 25 September 1967, and assigned to II Field Force stationed at Bien Hoa.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Its nucleus came from the LRRP platoon of the 173d Airborne Brigade, along with soldiers from the replacement stream.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Each of the two Field Force LRP companies had a strength of 230 men, and was commanded by a major.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In an apparent response to division commanders' tactical requirements, and bolstered by the combat effectiveness of the provisional LRRP units, in the winter of 1967 the Army authorized separate company designations for Long Range Patrol (LRP) units in divisions and detachments in separate brigades.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The divisional LRP companies were authorized 118 men and the brigade detachments 61 men.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The wholesale renaming of existing divisional LRP units occurred on 20 December 1967, in the 1st Cavalry, 1st Infantry, 4th Infantry, 9th Infantry, 23d (Americal), and 25th Infantry Divisions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] LRP detachments were created in the 199th Light Infantry Brigade on 10 January 1968, in the 173d Airborne Brigade on 5 February 1968, and in the 3d Brigade 82d Airborne Division and 1st Brigade 5th Mechanized Division on 15 December 1968.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 1 February 1969, the final period of the existence of these units began when the Department of the Army redesignated the LRP companies and detachments as lettered Ranger companies of the 75th Infantry Regiment under the Combined Arms Regimental System (CARS).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The third period ended when the Ranger companies were inactivated as their parent units were withdrawn from the war between November 1969 (starting with Company O, 3rd Brigade, 82nd Airborne Division) to 15 August 1972 (ending with Company H, 1st Cavalry Division).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 9 June 1972, H Company (Ranger) lost SGT Elvis Weldon Osborne Jr. and CPL Jeffrey Alan Maurer to enemy action.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Three other US soldiers were killed by non-hostile action that day, but SGT Osborne and CPL Maurer were the last US Army infantrymen killed on the ground, as well as the last Rangers killed in the Vietnam War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In January 1974, General Creighton Abrams, Army Chief of Staff, directed the formation of a Ranger battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Leuer was charged with activating, organizing, training and leading the first battalion sized Ranger unit since World War II.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Though the Vietnam War era Ranger companies of the 75th Infantry Regiment (Ranger), which drew their lineages from Merrill's Marauders, had all been deactivated (or soon would be), they passed their lineages and colors to these new battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 1st Battalion, which carried its legacy from Merrill's Marauders via Company C, 75th Infantry Regiment (Ranger) was activated and parachuted into Fort Stewart, Georgia, on 1 July 1974.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 2nd Battalion, which drew lineage from Company H, 75th Infantry (Ranger), followed shortly afterward with activation at Fort Lewis, Washington on 1 October 1974.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The 3rd Battalion and Headquarters Company were activated and received their colors on 3 October 1984, from Company F, 75th Infantry Regiment (Ranger) at Fort Benning, Georgia.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 3 February 1986, the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd Battalions of the 75th were consolidated with active and inactive units which carried the lineages of the World War II era: 1st, 2nd, 3rd, 4th, 5th, and 6th Ranger Battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The regiment as a whole was concurrently redesignated as the 75th Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The modern Ranger battalions were first called upon in 1980 when elements of 1st Ranger Battalion participated in Operation Eagle Claw, the Iranian hostage-rescue mission.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In October 1983, 1st and 2nd Ranger Battalions spearheaded Operation Urgent Fury, conducting a dangerous low-level parachute assault to seize Point Salines Airfield and rescue American citizens at True Blue Medical Campus in Grenada.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The entire 75th Ranger Regiment participated in Operation Just Cause, which lasted from December 1989 to January 1990.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Rangers spearheaded the action by conducting two important operations.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Simultaneous parachute assaults were conducted onto Torrijos/Tocumen International Airport, Rio Hato Airfield, and General Manuel Noriega's beach house to neutralize Panamanian Defense Forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers captured more than 1,014 prisoners of war and more than 18,000 weapons.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Elements of Company B, and 1st Platoon Company A, 1st Ranger Battalion, deployed to Saudi Arabia from 12 February 1991, to 15 April 1991, for Operation Desert Storm.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They conducted raids and provided a quick reaction force in cooperation with allied forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In December 1991, 1/75 and the Regimental headquarters deployed to Kuwait in a show of force called Operation Iris Gold.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers performed an airborne assault onto Ali Al Salem airfield, near Kuwait City, conducted a 50 km (31 mi) foot march through devastation (including mine fields) left from the ground campaign, conducted a live fire exercise, and left on foot.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In August 1993, elements of 3rd Ranger Battalion deployed to Somalia as "Task Force Ranger", part of Operation GOTHIC SERPENT designed to help United Nations forces attempting to bring order to the chaotic and starving nation.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 3 October 1993, the Rangers conducted a daylight raid with Delta Force.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They captured the high-value targets but the ensuing Battle of Mogadishu ended in chaos as the American forces were trapped for hours inside the city by Somalian militias, due to a series of planning and command errors, resulting in the death of 18 American soldiers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Rangers held improvised positions for nearly 18 hours, killing between 500 and 1,000 Somalis before American QRF, Pakistani, and Malaysian troops with armor rescued them and the American troops could retreat.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 1984, the 75th Ranger Regiment established a Regimental Reconnaissance Detachment (RRD).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 24 November 2000, the detachment deployed with a command-and-control element to Kosovo for Task Force Falcon.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By 2005, the unit—enlarged and renamed the Regimental Reconnaissance Company (RRC)—had become an elite special operations force and a member of Joint Special Operations Command.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 2006, the Regimental Reconnaissance Company was moved into the new Regimental Special Troops Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Several years into the war on terror, the 75th Ranger Regiment created a Regimental Special Troops Battalion (RSTB) to help switch from short-term "contingency missions" to continuous combat operations.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Activated on 17 July 2006, the RSTB conducts sustainment, intelligence, reconnaissance and maintenance missions that were previously accomplished by small detachments assigned to the Regimental Headquarters and then attached within each of the three Ranger battalions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The battalion consists of the Ranger Reconnaissance Company, the Ranger Communications Company (RCC), the Ranger Military Intelligence Company (RMIC), and the Ranger Selection and Training Company (RST&C).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The RSTB draws its lineage from Company N, 75th Infantry Regiment (back to Merrill's Marauders) and Company B, 1st Ranger Infantry Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] While the Ranger Regiment has traditionally been considered an elite light infantry force, its operations in Afghanistan and Iraq from 2001 to 2012 demonstrated its ability to conduct a full range of special operations missions.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In October 2007, a D Company was added to each of the three battalions of the 75th Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By 2012, the 75th Ranger Regiment was conducting sustained combat operations in multiple countries, deploying from multiple locations in the United States—an unprecedented task for the regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Rangers conducted combat operations with almost every deployed special operations, conventional, and coalition force in Operation Enduring Freedom and Operation Iraqi Freedom.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Ranger Regiment executed a wide range of operations, including airborne and air assaults into Afghanistan and Iraq, mounted infiltrations behind enemy lines, complex urban raids on high-value targets (HVTs), and rescue operations.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Ranger battalion operational tempo while deployed was high.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During one Afghanistan deployment, the 1st Ranger Battalion conducted more than 900 missions, captured nearly 1,700 enemy combatants (including 386 high-value targets), and killed more than 400 fighters.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By mid-2015 each Ranger battalion had completed its twentieth deployment to Afghanistan and Iraq.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After the events of September 11, 2001, Rangers were called into action for the war on terror.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 19 October 2001, 200 Rangers of 3rd Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment spearheaded ground forces by conducting an airborne assault to seize Objective Rhino during the 2001 invasion of Afghanistan, the opening battle of Operation Enduring Freedom – Afghanistan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Stonesifer became the first combat casualties in the war on terror when their MH-60L helicopter crashed at Objective Honda in Pakistan, a temporary staging site used by a company of Rangers from 3rd Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Ranger protection force teams were part of Task Force Sword, a black SOF unit whose primary objective was capturing or killing senior leaders and HVTs with al-Qaeda and the Taliban.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A squadron of Delta Force operatives, supported by Rangers from TF Sword, conducted an operation outside Kandahar at a location known as Objective Gecko; they missed the mission's target but killed some 30 Taliban fighters in a heavy firefight.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In November 2001, the 75th Ranger Regiment carried out its second combat parachute drop into Afghanistan: a platoon-sized Ranger security element, including the Regimental Reconnaissance Detachment Team 3 conducted the missions: Objective Wolverine, Raptor and Operation Relentless Strike.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the Battle of Tora Bora in December 2001, a CIA Jawbreaker team (a small group of CIA SAD ground branch operators) requested that the 3rd Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment be inserted into the mountains to block escape routes from Tora Bora to Pakistan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They would serve as an "anvil" while Special Forces with the Afghan Militia Forces would be the "hammer".
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] With the attached Air Force Combat Controllers, the Rangers could have directed airstrikes onto enemy concentrations or engaged them in ambushes, but their requests to do so were denied.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In March 2002, 35 Rangers from 1st Battalion, 75th Ranger Regiment had been assigned as QRF for all Task Force operations, but only half of the platoon was available for the Battle of Takur Ghar.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In the final days of Operation Anaconda, a mixed force of Rangers travelling in Blackhawk helicopters backed up operators from DEVGRU who intercepted a convoy of al-Qaeda fighters traveling in three SUVs via three MH-47Es.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A firefight left 16 al-Qaeda fighters dead and two seriously wounded and captured.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 18 August, Rangers and other coalition special forces joined the 82nd Airborne Division in Operation Mountain Sweep, carrying out five combat air assault missions in the area around the villages of Dormat and Narizah, south of Khowst and Gardez.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The force found an anti-aircraft gun, two 82mm mortars, recoilless rifles, rocket-propelled-grenade launchers, machine guns, small arms and ammunition for all of them; they also detained 10 people.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Later in 2002, TF 11 was replaced by a small JSOC element manned by SEALs and Rangers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 2003, after Khalid Sheikh Mohammed was arrested in a joint CIA-ISI operation in Pakistan, Rangers and 82nd Airborne Division troops helped transport him to a U.S. black site prison.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In summer 2005, during Operation Red Wings, a Ranger patrol retrieved HM2 Marcus Luttrell five days after he went missing.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In July 2006, in Helmand Province, two MH-47Es from 160th SOAR attempted to insert a combined strike element of DEVGRU, Rangers, and Afghan commandos so they could attack a compound.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] With some troops on the ground, a large insurgent force ambushed them; both helicopters were struck by small arms fire.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] One MH-47E pilot put his aircraft in the line of fire to protect the assault team disembarking from the other MH-47E, but was struck by an RPG and crash-landed without serious injury.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Ranger commander and an attached Australian commando organized an all-round defense while the other MH-47E held back the advancing insurgents until its Miniguns ran out of ammunition.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] An AC-130 Spectre joined the battle and kept the downed crew and passengers safe until a British Immediate Response Team helicopter recovered them.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The AC-130 then destroyed the MH-47E wreck, denying it to the Taliban.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Also that year, a six-man RRD (Regimental Reconnaissance Detachment) team from the 75th Ranger Regiment attached to the JSOC Task Force inserted into the Hindu Kush mountain range after intelligence indicated that an insurgent chief, Haqqani, would be entering Afghanistan from Pakistan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After establishing an OP almost 4,000 meters above sea level, the RRD team waited and watched for their target.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Insurgents arrived and began to fire on the Ranger team, whose attached JTAC called in an orbiting B-1B strategic bomber.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The airplane killed an estimated 100 insurgents, but not Haqqani.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In 2007, after a CIA source reported seeing Bin Laden in Tora Bora, many theater ISR assets were sent the area.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The initial plan based around a small helicopter assault force soon expanded to include Special Forces ODAs and a Ranger element to provide a cordon for the SEALs.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Eventually, the operation was launched under the cover of Air Force bombing, but after fruitless searching through the mountains, no sign of Bin Laden was found.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In June 2009, Army soldier Bowe Bergdahl was captured by the Taliban.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 8 October 2010, a troop from DEVGRU and two squads of Rangers tried to rescue Linda Norgrove, who was being held by the Taliban in compounds in the Korangal Valley.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The rescue mission failed when a DEVGRU operator accidentally killed Norgrove with a grenade.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] For actions between 14 and 16 November 2010, Charlie Company 1/75th, received the Valorous Unit Award for extraordinary heroism, combat achievement, and conspicuous gallantry.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] With ISAF's surge in Afghanistan at its peak in summer 2011, 1/75th (and Bravo Company in particular) received the Meritorious Unit Citation for actions during Operation Enduring Freedom between 15 May – 28 August 2011.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] These included conducting continuous combat operations, including time-sensitive raids and deliberate movement-to-contact operations in enemy-held terrain beyond reach of friendly forces in places like Khost, Paktika and Nangarhar Province.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Two Rangers from the battalion were killed during this time.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 20 July, Delta Force supported by Rangers and Afghan SOF elements were inserted by the 160th SOAR into the mountainous region of Sar Rowzah District, Paktika Province.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] They were immediately engaged by insurgents who were heavily armed with DShK HMGs and RPGs; during that night's fighting, about 30 insurgents were killed.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] As the sun rose, dozens of remaining insurgents who had been hiding in bunkers and caves became visible, and armed UAVs, AH-6s, and MH-60 DAPs flew in close air support, as did ground attack aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Fighting continued into a second day as bunkers and fighting positions were systematically cleared, some using then-recently issued Mk14 Antistructural Grenades.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] An estimated 80 to 100 Haqqani and foreign fighters were killed in the two-day battle.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Army Rangers began taking fire while trying to capture a senior Taliban leader in the Tangi Valley in Wardak province.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A CH-47 helicopter carrying 38 American and Afghan servicemen was dispatched to help, but was shot down by the Taliban.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] All 38 aboard died in the deadliest single incident for Americans in the Afghanistan campaign.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] During the 2003 invasion of Iraq, all three Ranger Battalions were assigned to a new Task Force whose goals were to seize key locations, conduct long-range special reconnaissance, and capture HVTs.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 24 March 2003, 3rd Battalion 75th Ranger Regiment conducted a combat drop onto H-1 Air Base, securing the site as a staging area for operations in western Iraq.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A company of Rangers and Royal Marines from 45 Commando flew into Iraq from Jordan to secure H-2 and H-3 airbases after they were captured by US, British and Australian SOF.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 26 March, B Company, 2/75th supported DEVGRU operators in the Objective Beaver raid on a suspected chemical and biological weapons site north of Haditha; they engaged numerous gunmen but found no chemical or biological weapons.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 1 April 2003, 290 Rangers from 1/75th and 2/75th helped rescue Private 1st Class Jessica Lynch; also that day, Delta Force and 3/75th captured the Haditha Dam and held it for five days.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After the invasion, the main 75th Ranger element deployed to Iraq carried out operations in northern Iraq and was based out of Mosul or Tikrit, supported by a small element of Delta Force operators.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The DEVGRU squadron were supported by a reinforced Ranger platoon as was the Delta Force squadron, all part of the overall effort by JSOC in Iraq.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 18 June 2003, Delta Force operators and Rangers flew from Mosul via helicopter to chase a vehicle convoy of Ba'ath Party Iraqis who were fleeing over the border into Syria; JSOC suspected that Saddam Hussein was part of the convoy so the convoy was destroyed by an AC-130 Spectre.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The operators then conducted a heliborne assault into a nearby compound that proved to be a Ba'athist safe house for ferrying former regime elements across the border.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The operators came under fire from Syrian border guards, leading to a firefight that left several Syrians dead and 17 captured.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Hussein was not in the convoy, but several of his cousins were.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 23 July 2005, in Baghdad, Rangers acted as a back-up force for the British Special Boat Service during Operation Marlborough.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 1 January 2006, Rangers raided a remote farmhouse outside Baghdad, capturing several gunmen without a fight and rescuing British freelance journalist Phillip Sands, who had been kidnapped a week earlier.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In Ramadi, the Rangers switched to riskier daylight raids after insurgents learned to move out of the city at night.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In November 2006, a new secret directive sanctioned by President Bush allowed U.S. forces in Iraq to kill or capture Iranian nationals if they were targeting coalition forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The directive reflected Hezbollah's success in the 2006 Lebanon War and Iran's defiance on its nuclear issue; the new mission was known by its acronym CII (Counter Iranian Influence).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The CII missions were given to Task Force 17, a new command based around the headquarters of an Army Special Forces group.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In June 2008, Rangers eliminated perhaps their highest-profile target yet: Abu Khalaf, deputy leader of al Qaeda in Iraq.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A reinforced platoon of Rangers assaulted the target house, codenamed Objective Crescent Lake.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] As the Ranger assault element placed their explosive breaching charges, two sentries on the roof of the house armed with AK-47 assault rifles approached them, who were then killed by an attached 4-man sniper team from the Ranger battalion's sniper platoon.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The assault element breached the house and methodically cleared each room; in one room, Rangers arrested a man and a woman.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] When the man reached under his clothing, the Rangers shot him, then the woman as she leapt on his body.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The man was found to be wearing a suicide-bomb vest filled with ball bearings.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Meanwhile, Khalaf ran to the road with a pistol and was shot dead by the Ranger snipers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Rangers also discovered a plan for a chemical weapon attack on a coalition base.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] By this time, the Rangers had sent an additional platoon to Iraq to help conduct a day-night raiding cycle, and conducted up to 100 missions in one three-month deployment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] After January 2009, the new Status of Forces Agreement (SOFA) required JSOC and Ranger operations to seek Iraqi judicial permission for each mission.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On the night of 18 April 2010, ISOF troops, supported by U.S. troops, raided a terrorist safe house near Tikrit in Iraq, the ISOF killed Abu Ayyub al-Masri and Abu Omar al-Baghdadi, the two leaders of ISI; 16 others were also arrested.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] A US UH-60 Blackhawk helicopter supporting the mission crashed, killing a Ranger NCO from 3/75th and wounding the aircrew.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In March 2006, DEVGRU operators and a Ranger element are alleged to have attacked an al-Qaeda training camp in North Waziristan in Pakistan.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In an operation reportedly named Operation Vigilant Harvest, they were flown across the Afghan-Pakistani border and killed as many as 30 terrorists, including the Chechen camp commandant Imam Asad.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The operation has been credited to the Pakistani Special Service Group.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 1 May 2011, a Ranger element was assigned to support Operation Neptune Spear, aimed at killing or capturing Osama bin Laden.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The Ranger element and additional SEALs in MH-47E Chinooks served as QRF; the Ranger element would also protect the FARP north of Abbottabad.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Following the successful completion of the operation, a Ranger team transported Bin Laden's body to the aircraft carrier USS *Carl Vinson* for burial at sea.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In November 2015, the U.S. military sent a company of Rangers to southeastern Afghanistan, as part of the post-ISAF phase of the war in Afghanistan, to help Afghan counter-terrorism forces destroy an al-Qaeda training camp in a "fierce fight" that lasted for several days.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On the evening of 26 April 2017, 50 Rangers from 3/75th joined 40 Afghan commandos in a joint US-Afghan raid on the headquarters of Abdul Hasib, the emir of ISIS-K, in a village in Achin District, Nangarhar Province.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] The force was flown into Mohmand Valley and within minutes were engaged in a heavy, close-quarter firefight with ISIL-KP militants.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] AC-130 gunships, Apache helicopters, F-16 fighters, and drones were called in.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] In the 3-hour firefight, two Rangers died (one each from C and D Companies, possibly from friendly fire) and one was wounded, while 35 ISIL-KP militants (including Abdul Hasib and an unspecified number of ISIL-KP leaders) were killed.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] U.S. officials took the unusual step of publicly talking about the Ranger deployment and where they are located to protect against them inadvertently coming under fire from forces fighting in the region or Turkish, Russian, or Syrian government forces.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 22 May 2017, the Ranger Regiment Military Intelligence Battalion was established to specialize in intelligence, surveillance, reconnaissance, cyber, and electronic warfare operations.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] Based at Fort Benning, it consists of the Military Intelligence Company (MICO), Cyber Electro Magnetic Activities company (CEMA), and Headquarters and Headquarters Company (HHC).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] It draws its lineage from Company P, 75th Infantry (back to Merrill's Marauders) and Company B, 2nd Ranger Infantry Battalion.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p01] On 26 October 2019, the Rangers, Delta Force, and the 160th SOAR killed ISIL leader Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] For new soldiers, RASP is conducted after applicants complete their basic Military Occupational Specialty course.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] After completing RASP, soldiers attend the Army parachutists course (Airborne School).
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] For soldiers, both enlisted and officer, who have completed their first tour of duty and meet the recruiting qualifications, a RASP date will be scheduled upon application and conditional acceptance to the 75th Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] RASP includes two levels of training: RASP 1 for junior non-commissioned officers and enlisted soldiers (pay grades E-1 through E-5) and RASP 2 for senior non-commissioned officers, officers, and warrant officers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Candidates train in physical fitness, marksmanship, small unit tactics, medical proficiency, and mobility.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Training is fast-paced and intense, ensuring Ranger candidates can handle continued training and worldwide operations upon reaching their assigned Ranger unit.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Throughout the course, candidates are screened to ensure that only the best soldiers are chosen for the Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] All candidates must meet the course requirements in order to serve in the Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Upon completion of RASP, candidates will don the tan beret and 75th Ranger Regiment Scroll.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Ranger Assessment & Selection Program 1 (RASP 1) is an 8-week selection course for junior non-commissioned officers and enlisted soldiers (pay grades E-1 through E-5) that is broken down into two phases.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Ranger candidates endure a grueling test of physical and mental endurance, road marches with rucksacks, land navigation, leadership skills, and weapons training—performed under continuous food and sleep deprivation.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Graduates have the advanced skills all Rangers are required to know to start their career with the 75th Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Phase 1 focuses more on the critical events and skill level 1 tasks and Phase 2 focuses on training in marksmanship, breaching, mobility, and physical fitness.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Ranger Assessment & Selection Program 2 (RASP 2) is a 21-day selection course for senior non-commissioned officers, officers, and warrant officers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Candidates' physical and mental capabilities are tested as they learn the special tactics, techniques and procedures of the Regiment, as well as learning the expectations of leading and developing young Rangers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] To maintain readiness, Rangers train constantly.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Rangers focus on the "Big 5": marksmanship, physical training, medical training, small unit tactics, and mobility.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Throughout their time in the Ranger Regiment, Rangers may attend many types of special schools and training.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Depending on occupation and job requirements, members of the 75th Ranger Regiment enjoy unparalleled access to countless military schools, including Jumpmaster, Sniper, Pathfinder, Military Freefall, Scuba, Survival-Evasion-Resistance-Escape (SERE), Special Operations Combat Medic and others.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Before serving as a leader in the Regiment, Rangers are also expected to attend and graduate Ranger School.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Members of the regiment may also get joint training and non-traditional military and civilian schooling.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Rangers are trained in "do-it-yourself" emergency medicine.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Based on the premise that 90% of deaths from wounds are suffered before reaching medical facilities and that there are not enough medics and doctors to go around, the regiment began to train Rangers to give themselves immediate, preliminary treatment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] A 2011 study found a 3 percent death rate from potentially survivable causes in the 75th Regiment between October 2001 and April 2010.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] That compares with a 24 percent rate in a previously reported set of U.S. military deaths in Iraq and Afghanistan, which included troops who didn't have Ranger-style training.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Army Special Operations Command unit, the Rangers maintain more stringent standards for their personnel.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] If at any point a Ranger is deemed to be failing to meet these standards he may be relieved and removed from the regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] This is commonly referred to as being RFSed, short for "Released For Standards".
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] A Ranger can be RFS'd for virtually any reason, ranging from lack of motivation to disciplinary problems.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Similarly, a Ranger physically incapable of performing his mission through prolonged illness or injury can also be removed from the regiment through a process referred to as RFM or "Relieved For Medical reasons".
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The 75th Ranger Regiment has been credited with numerous campaigns from World War II onwards.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] In World War II, they participated in 16 major campaigns, spearheading the campaigns in Morocco, Sicily, Naples-Foggia, Anzio, and Leyte.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] During the Vietnam War, they received campaign participation streamers for every campaign in the war.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The regiment received streamers with arrowheads (denoting conflicts they spearheaded) for Grenada and Panama.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The Rangers have earned six Presidential Unit Citations, nine Valorous Unit Awards, and four Meritorious Unit Commendation, the most recent of which were earned in Vietnam and Haditha, Iraq, respectively.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Sua Sponte, Latin for *Of their own accord* is the 75th Ranger Regiment's Regimental motto.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Contemporary rangers are triple-volunteers: for the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Army, for Airborne School, and for service in the 75th Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The motto "Rangers lead the way!" dates from 6 June 1944, during the Normandy Landings on Dog White sector of Omaha Beach.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Then Brigadier General Norman Cota (assistant CO of the 29th ID) calmly walked towards Maj.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Max Schneider (CO of the 5th Ranger Battalion) while under heavy machine gun fire and asked "What outfit is this?" Someone yelled "5th Rangers!" To this, Cota replied "Well then Goddammit, Rangers!
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Organizations define the term "Ranger" in different ways.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] For example, the annual "United States Army Best Ranger Competition," hosted by the Ranger Training Brigade, can be won by pairs of participants from the 75th Ranger Regiment, or by ranger-qualified entrants from other units in the U.S. military.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] For an individual to be inducted into the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Army Ranger Association's "Ranger Hall of Fame," they "must have served in a Ranger unit in combat or be a successful graduate of the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Army Ranger School." The Ranger Association further clarifies the type of unit: "A Ranger unit is defined as those Army units recognized in Ranger lineage or history." Acceptance into the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Army Ranger Association is limited to "Rangers that have earned the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] In June 2001, Army Chief of Staff General Eric Shinseki gave the order to issue black berets to regular soldiers.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] At the time, black berets were being worn exclusively by the Ranger Regiment.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] This created discontent within the 75th Ranger Regiment and even led to retired Rangers going on nationwide road marches to Washington, D.C. to protest against the decision.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Because there was not a Presidential authorization to the regiment for exclusive wear of the black beret, they switched to wearing a tan beret to preserve a unique appearance, tan being reflective of the buckskin worn by the men of Robert Rogers' Rangers during the French and Indian War.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] A memorandum for the purpose of changing the Ranger beret from black to tan was sent and approved in March 2002.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Press releases were issued and articles were published all over the nation about this change in headgear after it was formally announced by the Regimental Commander, Colonel P.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] In a private ceremony, past and present Rangers donned the tan beret on 26 July 2002.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The Army G-1 released a memorandum in October 2017 stating the following: WEAR OF THE TAN BERET OUTSIDE OF RANGER REGIMENT.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The memo from the Army G-1 expands authorization for wear of the Tan Beret in the following assignments: Headquarters elements of Combatant Commands, The Joint Staff, Department of the Army Headquarters, U.S.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Special Operations Command Joint Task Force, Theater Special Operations Command, and Joint Special Operations Command.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] The Tan Beret is authorized for Ranger-qualified Soldiers in the above listed assignments if they previously served in the 75th Ranger Regiment and departed on honorable terms.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] This was formalized in DA Pam 670–1 in January 2021.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Note: The above list accounts for 21 Colonels, missing are the first two.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Assignment dates are based on various biographies and may not all line up properly.
[src:door-breaching/75th-ranger-regiment-p02] Specific dates are based on reports of changes of command.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] An **officer's tool** (also known as an A-tool, rex tool, or lock puller) is a forcible entry device used by firefighters and other first responders.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] Officer's tools are designed to completely remove cylindrical locks from doors without causing major structural damage, allowing for direct access to the internal locking mechanism.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] Officer's tools can be used on any type of cylindrical lock, including rim locks, police locks, dead-bolts, or key-in-the-knob locks.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] A door that has had its lock cylinder removed can be outfitted with a new one afterward with only minor cosmetic damage, making officer's tools a less destructive alternative to other forcible entry devices like fireman's axes and battering rams.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] An officer's tool is composed of two primary sections: a heavily padded metal handle, and a two-sided metal head.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] One side of the head terminates in a flat striking surface, while the other features two metal prongs that taper outward.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] The angle of the prongs resembles an upper-case letter A, hence the name "A-tool".
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] Individual firefighters and fire departments may make modifications to officer's tools based on the types of locks and doors found in their area.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] A common modification involves adding metal spikes and forks to one end of the tool, similar to a Halligan bar.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] To remove a cylindrical lock from a door using an officer's tool, a user positions the head of the tool so that the exposed portion of the lock cylinder is directly between the tool's prongs.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] The user then holds the tool at a slight angle and hits the striking surface with a blunt object until it is firmly wedged in place around the lock.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] At this point, the lock cylinder can be pulled out of the door by using the handle of the officer's tool as a lever.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] The door will still be locked after the lock cylinder is removed, as the internal locking mechanism will still be intact.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] Many officer's tools come with shove knives capable of manipulating the locking mechanism directly, which ultimately unlocks and opens the door.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] Officer's tools are designed to cause minimal damage to doors and their internal locking mechanisms during the process of removing a lock cylinder.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] This is especially useful for doors that cannot be broken down easily or safely, such as those made of glass or outfitted with iron bars.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] A similar device, the smaller K-tool, is also capable of removing lock cylinders from doors.
[src:door-breaching/a-tool] K-tools can be used on locks that are too small or narrow to remove with an officer's tool, or on locks that are so flush with a door that the prongs of an officer's tool cannot grip it properly.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The idea of fighting forest fires from the air dates back at least as far as Friedrich Karl von Koenig-Warthausen's observations on seeing a blaze when overflying the Santa Lucia Range, California, in 1929.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of terminology has been used in the popular media for the aircraft (and methods) used in aerial firefighting.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The terms **airtanker** or **air tanker** generally refer to fixed-wing aircraft based in the United States; "airtanker" is used in official documentation.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The term "**waterbomber**" is used in some Canadian government documents for the same class of vehicles, though it sometimes has a connotation of amphibians.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] A wide variety of helicopters and fixed-wing aircraft are used for aerial firefighting.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service and Bureau of Land Management own, lease, or contract for nearly 1,000 aircraft each fire season, with annual expenditures in excess of US$250 million in recent years".
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters may be fitted with tanks (helitankers) or they may carry buckets.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Some helitankers, such as the Erickson AirCrane, are also outfitted with a front-mounted foam cannon.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Buckets are usually filled by submerging or dipping them in lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or portable tanks.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The most popular of the buckets is the flexible Bambi Bucket.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Tanks can be filled on the ground (by water tenders or truck-mounted systems) or water can be siphoned from lakes, rivers, reservoirs, or a portable tank through a hanging snorkel.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Currently the world's largest helicopter, the Mil Mi-26, uses a Bambi bucket.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Mendocino Air Tanker Squad formed by Joseph Bolles Ely in 1956 was the first such unit in the United States to drop water and retardant on fires.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Based at the Willows-Glenn County Airport it soon led the way for other agencies to form similar squads.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Though World War II- and Korean War-era bombers were for a long time the mainstay of the aerial firefighting fleet, newer purpose-built tankers have since come online.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The smallest are the Single Engine Air Tankers (SEATs).
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] These are agricultural sprayers that generally drop about 800 US gallons (3,000 L) of water or retardant.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Examples include the Air Tractor AT-802, which can deliver around 800 gallons of water or fire retardant solution in each drop, and the Soviet Antonov An-2 biplane.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Both of these aircraft can be fitted with floats that scoop water from the surface of a body of water.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Similar in configuration to the World War II–era Consolidated PBY Catalina, the Canadair CL-215 and its derivative the CL-415 are designed and built specifically for firefighting.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Croatian Air Force uses six CL-415s as well as six AT 802s for firefighting purposes.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Conair also converted a number of Convair 580 and Fokker F27 Friendship turboprop airliners to air tankers.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The largest aerial firefighter ever used is a Boeing 747 aerial firefighter, known as the Global Supertanker, that can carry 19,600 US gallons (74,200 L) fed by a pressurized drop system.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Supertanker was deployed operationally for the first time in 2009, fighting a fire in Spain.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The tanker made its first American operation on August 31, 2009, at the Oak Glen Fire.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] It has since been replaced by a Boeing 747-400.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Another wide body jetliner that is currently being used as an air tanker is the modified McDonnell Douglas DC-10-30 operated by the 10 Tanker Air Carrier company as the DC-10 Air Tanker.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] It can carry up to 12,000 US gallons (45,400 L) of fire fighting retardant.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Russian Ministry of Emergency Situations operates convertible-to-cargo Ilyushin Il-76 airtankers that have been operating with 11,000-US-gallon (41,600 L) tanking systems, and several Beriev Be-200 jet powered amphibian aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Be-200 can carry a maximum payload of about 12,000 litres (3,200 US gal) of water, making "scoops" in suitable stretches of water in 14 seconds.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Bombardier's Dash 8 Q Series aircraft are the basis of new, next-generation air tankers.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Cascade Aerospace has converted two pre-owned Q400s to act as part-time water bomber and part-time transport aircraft for France's Sécurité Civile, while Neptune Aviation is converting a pre-owned Q300 as a prototype to augment its Lockheed P-2 Neptune aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Sécurité Civile also operates twelve Canadair CL-415 and nine Conair Turbo Firecat aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Neptune Aviation also currently operates converted British Aerospace 146 jetliners as air tankers.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The BAe 146 can carry up to 3,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray USA Ltd. of Chico, California has also converted the BAe 146 jetliner to the role of air tanker.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Another modern-era passenger aircraft that has now been converted for aerial firefighting missions in the U.S. is the McDonnell Douglas MD-87 jetliner operated by Erickson Aero Tanker.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The MD-87 can carry up to 4,000 gallons of fire fighting retardant.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Coulson Aviation unveiled a Boeing 737-300 firefighting conversion in May 2017.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Six aircraft have been purchased from Southwest Airlines for the RADS system conversion which was planned to enter service in December 2017.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The 737 aircraft is smaller than the C-130Q which allows for a wider range of airfields to be utilized.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Britt Coulson further stated the aircraft will be able to retain the current seat and galley configuration for tanker operations.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] On 22 November 2018, the 737 was used for the first time to fight a fire near Newcastle, Australia.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] In July 2022, Airbus tested the aerial firefighting capacity of the A400M using a roll-on/roll-off kit comprising a 20-tonne water tank and piping allowing the load to be expelled from the end of the cargo ramp.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] All links, citations and data sources are listed in the paragraph above.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] For accident and grounding citations, see paragraph below table.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Other former military aircraft utilized as firefighting air tankers in the U.S. in the past included the B-17 and the PB4Y-2, a version of the B-24.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Lead Plane function directs the activities of the airtankers by both verbal target descriptions and by physically leading the airtankers on the drop run.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The leadplane is typically referred to as a "Bird Dog" in Canada or "Supervision" aircraft in Australia.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The O-2 Skymaster, Cessna 310 and OV-10 Bronco have been used as spotter and lead plane platforms.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Ontario Ministry of Natural Resources has also used the Cessna 337.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Beechcraft Baron was long used as a leadplane or air attack ship, but most were retired in 2003; more common now is the Beechcraft King Air and the Twin Commander 690.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] A Cessna Citation 500 jet owned by Air Spray (1967) LTd. was used by the British Columbia Ministry of Forests beginning in 1995 and used for two fire seasons to lead the very fast Electra L188 air tanker to the fires.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] This was the first time a jet aircraft was used as a lead plane or "bird dog".
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Department of Parks and Wildlife in Western Australia operates a fleet of nine American Champion Scouts 8GCBC during the summer months as spotter aircraft and Air Attack platforms.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The Provinces of Alberta and British Columbia and the Yukon Territories contract to supply Twin Commander 690 as bird dog aircraft for their air tanker fleets.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Air Spray owns 9 Twin Commander 690 for use as bird dog aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] In the United States, most of these aircraft are privately owned and contracted to government agencies, and the National Guard and the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Marines also maintain fleets of firefighting aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Forest Service (USFS) and the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) announced that they were cancelling contracts with operators of 33 heavy airtankers.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] They cited liability concerns and an inability to safely manage the fleet after the wing failure and resulting crash of a C-130A Hercules in California and a PB4Y-2 in Colorado during the summer of 2002.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Both aged aircraft broke up in flight due to catastrophic fatigue cracks at the wing roots.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] After subsequent third-party examination and extensive testing of all USFS contracted heavy airtankers, three companies were awarded contracts and now maintain a combined fleet of 23 aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Borate salts used in the past to fight wildfires have been found to sterilize the soil and be toxic to animals so are now prohibited.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Newer retardants use ammonium sulfate or ammonium polyphosphate with attapulgite clay thickener or diammonium phosphate with a guar gum derivative thickener.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants often contain wetting agents, preservatives and rust inhibitors and are colored red with ferric oxide or fugitive color to mark where they have been dropped.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Brand names of fire retardants for aerial application include Fortress and Phos-Chek.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Some water-dropping aircraft carry tanks of a guar gum derivative to thicken the water and reduce runoff.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Helicopters can hover over the fire and drop water or retardant.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The S-64 Helitanker has microprocessor-controlled doors on its tank.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] The doors are controlled based on the area to be covered and wind conditions.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Fixed-wing aircraft must make a pass and drop water or retardant like a bomber.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Water is not usually dropped directly on flames because its effect is short-lived.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Fire retardants are not typically used to extinguish the fire, but instead are used to contain the fire, or slow it down to allow ground crews to contain it.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Because of this, retardants are usually dropped in front of or around a moving fire, rather than directly on it, creating a firebreak.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Aerial firefighting is most effectively used in conjunction with ground-based efforts, as aircraft are only one weapon in the firefighting arsenal.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] However, there have been cases of aircraft extinguishing fires long before ground crews were able to reach them.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] Some firefighting aircraft can refill their tanks in mid-flight, by flying down to skim the surface of large bodies of water.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] This is particularly useful in rural areas where flying back to an airbase for refills may take too much time.
[src:door-breaching/aerial-firefighting] In 2002 an Ontario CL-415 crew was able to refill 100 times within a 4-hour mission, delivering 162,000 US gallons (613,240 L) or 1,350,000 pounds (612 t) of water on a fire near Dryden, Ontario (June 1, 2002 Dryden fire # 10 Tanker #271 civil ident C-GOGE).
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports with scheduled passenger flights are obliged to have firefighters and firefighting apparatus on location ready for duty any time aircraft operate.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports may have regulatory oversight by an arm of their individual national governments or voluntarily under standards of the International Civil Aviation Organization.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the mass casualty potential of an aviation emergency, the speed with which emergency response equipment and personnel arrive at the scene of the emergency is of paramount importance.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Their arrival and initial mission to secure the aircraft against all hazards, particularly fire, increases the survivability of the passengers and crew on board.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airport firefighters have advanced training in the application of firefighting foams, dry chemical and clean agents used to extinguish burning aviation fuel in and around an aircraft in order to maintain a path for evacuating passengers to exit the fire hazard area.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Further, should fire either be encountered in the cabin or extend there from an external fire, the ARFF responders must work to control/extinguish these fires as well.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Primary to the hazard mitigation and safe evacuation of ambulatory passengers is the need to perform rescue operations.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Passengers unable to extricate themselves must be removed from the aircraft and provided medical care.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] This process is extremely labor-intensive, requiring both firefighters and support personnel.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the nature of a mass casualty incident, rescue workers employ triage to classify the victims and direct their efforts where they can maximize survival.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Subsequent to the emergency being declared under control, the ARFF function reverts to one of protecting the scene, eliminating any peripheral or slowly evolving hazards and assisting to preserve the scene for investigators.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In 2016, an Emirati fire fighter died from burns when trying to fight the fire in the Emirates Flight 521 crash.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Due to the rarity of aircraft fires, firefighters often have other usual duties such as luggage loaders or security guards, which they have to abandon at fire alarms.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Specialized fire apparatus are required for the ARFF function, the design of which is predicated on many factors but primarily: speed, water-carrying capacity, off-road performance, and agent discharge rates.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Since an accident could occur anywhere on or off airport property, sufficient water and other agents must be carried to contain the fire to allow for the best possibility of extinguishment, maximum possibility for evacuation and/or until additional resources arrive on the scene.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] They also must wear self-contained breathing apparatus to provide a source of clean air, enabling them to work in the presence of smoke or other super-heated gases, such as when making entry into the burning cabin of an aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) mandates ARFF operations at all U.S. airports that serve scheduled passenger air carriers.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] These are the only civilian fire protection services that are specifically regulated by any governmental entity.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military bases may have their own ARFF services with specialized duties and training.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Airports required to have ARFF services are inspected at least annually by the FAA for compliance with FAR, Part 139.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] Military ARFF operations must meet the mission requirements for their individual branch of the service.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] In many cases the FAA will perform the investigatory duties after an incident, but in instances where significant injuries or any fatal accident the National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) will investigate and the ARFF contingent will assist where needed.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] An index is assigned to each FAA Part 139 certificate holder based on a combination of the air carrier aircraft length and the average number of daily departures.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest air carrier aircraft at the airport has five or more average daily departures, the matching index is used.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] If the longest aircraft has less than five average daily departures, the next lower index is used.
[src:door-breaching/aircraft-rescue-and-firefighting] That index determines the required number of ARFF vehicles and required amount of extinguishing agents.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] An **airport crash tender** (known in some countries as an **airport fire appliance**) is a specialised fire engine designed for use in aircraft firefighting at aerodromes, airports, and military air bases.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] They can be mounted on 4x4, 6x6, or even 8x8 wheeled chassis.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] In order to decrease their turning radius, all four of the 8x8 wheeled unit's front wheels may be steerable.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Newer airport crash tenders also incorporate twin-agent nozzles/injection systems to inject a stream of Purple-K dry chemical into the AFFF firefighting foam stream, helping to extinguish the fire faster.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Some also have Halotron tanks with handlines for situations that require a clean agent to be utilized.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] These features allow airport crash tenders to reach an aircraft quickly, and rapidly put out large fires with jet fuel involved.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Some tenders have an elevated extended extinguishing arm capable of raising a water/foam cannon up to about 10–20 m (33–66 ft).
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Some can then puncture superficial structures of an aeroplane to fight a fire inside the fuselage.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] The International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) has given standards and recommended practices on rescue fire fighting categories of civil aerodromes.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] National aviation authorities may have given even further requirements on aerodrome rescue and fire services.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] The rescue fire services are based on a critical aircraft size based on a statistical analysis of movements (take-offs and landings) on the airport.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] There are also minimum category levels based on e.g. the number of seats in the critical aircraft.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Depending on the airport category, the standards determine the minimum number of rescue fire-fighting vehicles.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] In addition, requirements are given on the water and foam capacities, discharge rates for foam solutions, and minimum dry chemical powder (complementary agent) amounts, reserve stocks of fire fighting agents, ability to operate on rough terrain, and acceleration of the air crash tenders.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] The end of each runway has to be reached in a response time of two minutes or less, and any part of the movement area has to be achieved in a response time not exceeding three minutes.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Airport rescue and firefighting services operate many specialist vehicles to provide emergency cover at airports.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] Domestic appliances are similar in function and appearance to fire appliances operated by local fire services.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] They are not as large or as heavy as airport crash tenders.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] The units are ordinarily used to respond to fire incidents in airport terminal buildings but also respond to aircraft incidents.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] The appliances carry breathing apparatus, rescue equipment, firefighting media, ladders, cutting equipment, etc.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] "*First attack*" or "*rapid intervention vehicles*" (RIV).
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] RIVs are normally smaller, nimble fire appliances capable of quick acceleration and high speed.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] They carry less equipment than domestic appliances and crash tenders but arrive first on scene at aircraft incidents to begin rescue and firefighting operations whilst heavier and larger units approach.
[src:door-breaching/airport-crash-tender] *General purpose vehicles* (such as a fire chief's car or general purpose or incident support vehicles).
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The **Association of the United States Army** (**AUSA**) is a private, non-profit organization that serves as the professional association of the United States Army.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Founded in 1950, it has 121 chapters worldwide.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Membership is open to everyone, not just Army personnel, nor is membership mandatory for soldiers.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The organization publishes *ARMY Magazine* and the *Green Book*.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The current president is retired Army General Robert Brooks Brown.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Membership in AUSA is not just open to all Army ranks and all components are represented—including Regular Army, National Guard, Army Reserve, Government Civilians, Retirees, Wounded Warriors, Veterans but to concerned citizens and family members.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] AUSA welcomes anyone who subscribes to the philosophy of a strong national defense with special concern for the Army.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Community businesses and defense industry companies are also vital and contributing members of AUSA.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Other membership categories include Community Partners and National Partners (for defense industry businesses).
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Membership in AUSA includes a subscription to *ARMY Magazine* received monthly, including the *Green Book*, which is published in October of each year.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The *Green Book* is an almanac of articles from Army leadership and reference information about America's Army worldwide.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Members also receive *AUSA Extra* a weekly digital newspaper featuring the latest news about the Army and the association.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The AUSA Annual Meeting & Exposition is held each year in the Washington DC Metro area.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Driscoll, the United States Secretary of the Army, announced that in 2025, the United States Army has partnered with Y Combinator to bring in small companies to the conference and host a pitch-style competition to drive innovation.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] AUSA has 121 chapters worldwide, which develop programs and activities that provide community support for the US Army through individual and corporate members.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Chapters serve as the liaison between the Army and local civilian communities.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Typical chapter activities include general membership meetings with high-profile guest speakers, community involvement events and special events honoring the Army and outstanding soldiers.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The Association of the United States Army presents a number of soldiers, civil servants, and volunteers with national awards at its Annual Meeting.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] In addition, local chapters also give a variety of awards to local soldiers, Army civilians, and volunteers, as well as managing scholarships programs benefiting local students and soldiers.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Established in 1960, the George Catlett Marshall Medal is AUSA's highest honor, and is awarded annually for selfless service to the United States.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Past recipients include Colin Powell, Madeleine Albright, Kenneth Fisher, and George H.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Established in 1965, the General Creighton W.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Abrams Medal is awarded annually to the individual or group who has done the most to foster the advancement of the United States Army during the past year.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Past recipients include Daniel Inouye, William E.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Drexel Biddle Medal is awarded annually to the individual who has contributed most significantly to AUSA's mission over the previous year, often honoring AUSA's most diligent volunteers.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Becton Jr., Paik Sun-yup, and William G.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Established in 2000, the Sergeant Major of the Army William G.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Bainbridge Medal is awarded annually to the noncommissioned officer contributing most to the United States Army Noncommissioned Officer Corps.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Martinez, CSM Andrew McFowler, and Richard A.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Dixon Award, established in 1989, is presented annually for distinguished service in the industrial community resulting in outstanding contributions to national defense.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Past recipients include Linda Hudson, Marillyn Hewson, and Norman R.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] The Major General James Early Rudder Medal is given to a current or former member of the U.S.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] Army Reserve for advancing a seamless and component-integrated Army.
[src:door-breaching/association-of-the-united-states-army] McLain Medal given to a current or former member of the National Guard for advancing a seamless and component-integrated Army.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] A **backdraft** (North American English), **backdraught** (British English) or **smoke explosion** is the abrupt burning of superheated gases in a fire caused when oxygen rapidly enters a hot, oxygen-depleted environment; for example, when a window or door to an enclosed space is opened or broken.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Backdrafts are typically seen as a blast of smoke and/or flame out of an opening of a building.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Backdrafts present a serious threat to firefighters.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] There is some debate concerning whether backdrafts should be considered a type of flashover.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] When material is heated enough, it begins to break down into smaller compounds, including flammable or even explosive gas, typically hydrocarbons.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] This is called pyrolysis, and does not require oxygen.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] If oxygen is also provided, then the hydrocarbons can combust, starting a fire.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] If material undergoing pyrolysis is later given sufficient oxygen, the hydrocarbons will ignite and, therefore, combustion takes place.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] A backdraft can occur when a compartment fire has little or no ventilation.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Due to this, little or no oxygen can flow into the compartment.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Then, because fires reduce oxygen, the oxygen concentration decreases.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] When the oxygen concentration becomes too low to support combustion, some or all of the combustion switches to pyrolysis.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Nonetheless, the hydrocarbons and smoke (primarily particulate matter) remain at a temperature hot enough to auto-ignite.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] The colour and movement of smoke is used by firefighters to infer fire conditions, including the risk of backdraft.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] This is an indication that the room lacks enough oxygen to permit oxidation of the soot particles.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Firefighters often look to see if there is soot on the inside of windows and in any cracks in the window (caused e.g. by the heat).
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] The windows may also have a slight vibration due to varying pressure within the compartment due to intermittent combustion.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] If firefighters discover a room sucking air into itself, for example through a crack, they generally evacuate immediately, because this is a strong indication that a backdraft is imminent.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Due to pressure differences, puffs of smoke are sometimes drawn back into the enclosed space from which they emanated, which is how the term *backdraft* originated.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Backdrafts are very dangerous, often surprising even experienced firefighters.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] The most common tactic used by firefighters to defuse a potential backdraft is to ventilate a room from its highest point, allowing the heat and smoke to escape without igniting.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] In common usage, the term flashover describes the near-simultaneous ignition of material caused by heat attaining the autoignition temperature of the combustible material and gases in an enclosure.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Flashovers according to this narrower definition, i.e. those caused by rising temperatures, would not be considered backdrafts since backdrafts are caused by the introduction of oxygen into an enclosed space with conditions already suitable for ignition, and are thus caused by chemical change.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] Backdrafts were publicized by the 1991 movie *Backdraft*, in which a serial arsonist in Chicago uses them as a means of assassinating conspirators in a scam.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] In the film adaptation of Stephen King's *1408*, the protagonist Mike Enslin induces one as a last-ditch effort to kill the room.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] The term is also used and is the title of a scene in the 2012 video game *Root Double: Before Crime * After Days*.
[src:door-breaching/backdraft] In the second book of the light novel series Imperial Reincarnation: I Came, I Saw, I Survived, the character Carmine uses a magically produced backdraft to defend himself against an assassination attempt.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The simplest solution is to check the door knob first.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Utilizing a breaching tool is unnecessary if the door is unlocked and easy to open.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] If the door is locked, breachers can attempt to force inward-opening doors with a strong kick.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The breacher will aim to hit the door near the locking mechanism, but not kick the doorknob itself as one can easily twist an ankle doing so.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Other methods, like ballistic breaching, can be supplemented afterward with a kick to force the door in.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Mechanical breaching can be used to defeat the latch, lock, hinges, or door itself and methods can vary from minimally destructive to very destructive.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Lockpicking with traditional lock picks is a minimally destructive method but is relatively slow and requires a trained operator.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Alternatively, a snap gun can be used to defeat the lock, which requires less skill and training.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Tools can also be used to bypass the lock itself; for example, shims can be used to unlock padlocks by directly interacting with the bolts holding the padlock's shackle in place.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] For doors, a shove knife can be wedged into the door jamb and open the latch bolt without having to deal with the lock itself.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Another option is to remove the cylinder lock from the door using instruments like an A-tool or K-tool; these methods also allow the door to be closed and re-locked afterward.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] More dynamic methods use significantly more force to break the lock or door.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Tools like the Halligan bar, pry bar, Denver tool, Kelly tool, claw tool, or "the pig", can be used to lever a door open.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Other tools, like sledgehammers or battering rams (like the enforcer), concentrate a large amount of kinetic force on the door to defeat the locking mechanism.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Padlocks and similar barriers can also be removed with bolt cutters.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Doors can also be breached by cutting through the material of the door itself with a circular saw, though this is much slower.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Although not strictly pertaining to door breaching, windows can also be breached to gain entry using a "break and rake" tool.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] This tool first "breaks" the window, then "rakes" aside pieces of broken glass as well as any window frame.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Hydraulic breaching utilizes a hydraulic system to force the door open.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] These systems include hydraulic rescue tools (of the type used to extract people entrapped in vehicle wreckages) as well as specialized tools made specifically for door breaching.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The hydraulic device may be powered manually, pneumatically, or electrically.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Ballistic breaching uses a projectile weapon to breach an opening.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Weapons used can range from various small arms to a 120mm tank gun, which will easily breach most obstacles, though the force involved may violate the rules of engagement.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] In practice, shotguns are usually used to destroy the latch and lock, or the hinges of the door.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] While in theory other firearms can be used, handguns are usually underpowered and rifles are less effective than the shotgun and pose a far higher risk of ricochet and collateral injury.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Short pump-action shotguns are commonly used as they are less bulky and easier to maneuver.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The shotgun can be used as a primary weapon by the breacher or be dedicated solely for breaching.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] If the latter, the shotgun can be holstered or slung in a harness when not in use.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] There are also breaching shotgun systems which can be mounted to a rifle to avoid the issue of managing two weapons.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Examples include the KAC Masterkey, Ciener Ultimate Over/Under, M26 MASS, Metal Storm MAUL, and Crye Six12.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Most shotgun ammunition can be used for breaching, though the risk of injury varies with type.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Of the available shotgun ammunition, shotgun slugs pose the highest risk, as they will retain significant energy to cause lethal wounds well after they have penetrated the door.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Buckshot is far safer and birdshot even more so, as the multiple small projectiles disperse quickly after penetration, reducing the chances of causing a lethal wound (though more shots may be required if using birdshot).
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The safest option is a frangible round such as the TESAR or Hatton round, which turns to dust upon penetrating the door and disperses completely upon exit, though, these rounds are also more expensive.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Breaching a door with the fewest shots possible is faster and reduces the chance of collateral damage.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Attacking the latch and lock is easiest, as it requires fewer shots and is easiest to target, whereas attacking the hinges requires more shots, and the hinges may not be visible from the outside.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] According to US urban warfare doctrine, the breaching operation is performed with the muzzle in contact with the door, or as close as possible, and angled downwards at a 45-degree angle.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] This process provides the best chance of hitting the desired point, while minimizing risk to occupants of the room being breached.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Muzzle attachments are available on some specialized breaching shotguns to facilitate this operation, by holding the barrel securely in place while providing a slight standoff to allow powder gases to escape.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] For a breach on the latch side, US doctrine calls for two shots to be fired at a point halfway between the lock or handle and the door frame to hit the lock's bolt, and then an attempt made to open the door.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] If the door cannot be opened, the process would need to be quickly repeated.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] A hinge-side breach calls for a total of three shots per hinge followed by an attempt to open the door.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Explosive breaching can be the fastest method, though it is also the most dangerous, to both the breachers and the room occupants.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Depending on the situation, explosive breaching is potentially slower than a ballistic breach due to the large standoff required (if there is no cover available).
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Breaching can be performed with a specially formed breaching charge placed in contact with the door, or with various standoff breaching devices, such as specialized rifle grenades like the SIMON breach grenade.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Explosive breaching usually breaches doors via one of several mechanisms: pushing the door inward (e.g. water charge), cutting through the door's material (e.g. linear shaped charge), defeating the lock or hinge, or general blast effects (i.e. explosives in contact with door).
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The explosive breaching charges used can range from highly focused methods, such as detcord, plastic explosives, or strip shaped charges that explosively cut through doors or latches, to large satchel charges, containing 20 pounds (9.1 kg) of C-4, that can breach even reinforced concrete bunkers.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The explosive method of entry can be a safe and effective tool in the hands of qualified breachers.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Whereas in the past, the rule of thumb was to use "P for plenty" if unsure whether adequate explosives were being applied, breachers today strive to use the least amount of explosive necessary to secure penetration into a target.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Using the minimum amount of explosives necessary produces the least shockwave which reduces standoff distance for the team, potential injury to occupants, and damage to the general vicinity.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] This can be accomplished by calculating the net explosive weight (NEW) which is the equivalent weight of TNT that would be required to effect entry through various obstacles like reinforced concrete, plywood of various thicknesses, steel doors of various thicknesses, etc.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The net explosive weights of commonly used explosives is recorded so breachers can refer to these values when calculating how much of a certain explosive would be needed to meet the necessary NEW.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The minimum standoff distance or minimum safe distance is the minimum distance from the explosive charge the breachers must be to avoid serious injury from overpressure.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] The minimum standoff distance is calculated based on the amount and type of explosive placed and is used to ensure that breachers do not experience greater than 4 psi (28 kPa) of overpressure.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Hearing damage can occur at 3.4 psi (23 kPa) or greater, but this is negated by using hearing protection.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Blast overpressure dissipates quickly in open air so it is ideal for creating standoff distance but it is not always available depending on tactical circumstances.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Conversely, overpressure within structures is especially troublesome as sound reflects off walls and ceilings.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Reduced minimum safe distance can be achieved by staying off axis from the explosive (including around a corner) or having a physical obstacle between the team and the explosive (like a wall or a blast blanket).
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Minimum safe distance and effectiveness of explosives can be augmented by tamping.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] This entails laying materials over the explosive to help direct the blast toward the door or material that needs to be breached.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Tamping can be done with sandbags, rubble, or even filled water containers.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] A *water charge* refers to an explosive breach charge that is tamped with water, typically consisting of two water bags and some detcord in the middle.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Soldiers hit upon the idea to use saline-filled IV bags, which are commonly carried by medics, for such tamping and the practice spread to police organizations as well.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] While effective, these water charges are not without their downsides.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Water is heavy and difficult to transport; it also makes the explosive charge heavier and more difficult to place.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Special adhesives or a prop stick may be necessary to hold the charge in place.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] This adds complexity to the breach and the prop stick (if one is used) can become shrapnel.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] After detonation, the water will splash over the breach point and can present a slip hazard.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Additionally, lower-than-freezing temperatures will render water unusable as a tamping agent.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] As a result, synthetic gel tamping agents have been developed as alternatives.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] In addition to their tactical use, explosives have been used for search and rescue and other critical access situations.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] Thermal breaching is one of the least common techniques and also one of the slowest.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] It involves the use of a cutting torch to cut through metal doors.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] While man-portable cutting torch systems exist, they still weigh a significant amount.
[src:door-breaching/door-breaching] A lightweight single-use cutting torch has been developed which does not require the bulky, heavy oxygen cylinders typically employed by such systems, though, the torch has a limited use time and multiple torches may be required to complete a cut.
